{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657261"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:25:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:25:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19159"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19159"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11893"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82321"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11893"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19159"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67519"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27856"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28130"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82321"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic asking about her nasal decongestant spray. She reports that it worked well initially but has become less effective over the past few days despite using it more frequently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes a rapid decrease in therapeutic response to repeated drug administration over a short time period, requiring increasing doses to achieve the same effect.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following pharmacological terms best describes this phenomenon?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chronotropism","Idiosyncrasy","Tachyphylaxis","Teratogenesis","Xenobiosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis clinical scenario describes the classic presentation of \u003Cstrong\u003Etachyphylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the rapid development of tolerance to a drug\u0027s effects over a short time period, often within hours or days. This is particularly common with nasal decongestants like pseudoephedrine or oxymetazoline, where repeated use leads to diminishing effectiveness and potential rebound congestion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronotropism\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the effect of a substance on heart rate. While some sympathomimetics can affect heart rate, this term does not describe the phenomenon of diminishing drug response over time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdiosyncrasy\u003C/strong\u003E refers to an unexpected or unusual reaction to a drug that is peculiar to a specific individual. This term describes unpredictable drug responses that differ from the typical therapeutic effect, not the gradual loss of effectiveness described in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETeratogenesis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the process by which birth defects are produced during embryonic development, typically due to exposure to certain drugs or environmental factors during pregnancy. This is not relevant to the clinical scenario presented.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EXenobiosis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the process by which an organism detoxifies or metabolises foreign substances. While drug metabolism is relevant to pharmacology, this term does not specifically describe the rapid development of drug tolerance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these pharmacological terms is crucial for healthcare providers as they help describe and predict drug effects and guide appropriate prescribing practices. In the case of tachyphylaxis to nasal decongestants, patient education about limited duration of use is essential to prevent this common problem.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tachyphylaxis refers to the rapid decrease in response to repeated drug doses over a short time period, distinct from tolerance which develops over longer periods.","Understanding complex pharmacological terminology is essential for safe prescribing and drug monitoring.","Tachyphylaxis commonly occurs with sympathomimetic drugs such as pseudoephedrine."],"references":["Waller, D. G., \u0026 Hitchings, A. W. (2021). Medical Pharmacology and Therapeutics E-Book: Medical Pharmacology and Therapeutics E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Tashjian, A. H., \u0026 Armstrong, E. J. (2011). Principles of pharmacology: the pathophysiologic basis of drug therapy. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67519"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19159"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67519"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-29T15:38:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-29T15:39:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11893"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82321"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"de